Author-Name: EFRAIM BENMELECH 
Author-Name: TOBIAS J. MOSKOWITZ 
Title: The Political Economy of Financial Regulation: Evidence from U.S. State Usury Laws in the 19th Century 
Abstract:
 Financial regulation was as hotly debated a political issue in the 19th
 century as it is today. We study the political economy of state usury laws
 in 19th century America. Exploiting the wide variation in regulation,
 enforcement, and economic conditions across states and time, we find that
 usury laws when binding reduce credit and economic activity, especially
 for smaller firms. We examine the motives of regulation and find that
 usury laws coincide with other economic and political policies favoring
 wealthy political incumbents, particularly when they have more voting
 power. The evidence suggests financial regulation is driven by private
 interests capturing rents from others rather than public interests
 protecting the underserved. Copyright (c) 2010 the American Finance Association. 
