Author-Name: PAUL BROCKMAN 
Author-Name: XIUMIN MARTIN 
Author-Name: EMRE UNLU 
Title: Executive Compensation and the Maturity Structure of Corporate Debt 
Abstract:
 Executive compensation influences managerial risk preferences through
 executives' portfolio sensitivities to changes in stock prices (delta) and
 stock return volatility (vega). Large deltas discourage managerial
 risk-taking, while large vegas encourage risk-taking. Theory suggests that
 short-maturity debt mitigates agency costs of debt by constraining
 managerial risk preferences. We posit and find evidence of a negative
 (positive) relation between CEO portfolio deltas (vegas) and
 short-maturity debt. We also find that short-maturity debt mitigates the
 influence of vega- and delta-related incentives on bond yields. Overall,
 our empirical evidence shows that short-term debt mitigates agency costs
 of debt arising from compensation risk. Copyright (c) 2010 The American Finance Association. 
