Author-Name: PETER ILIEV 
Title: The Effect of SOX Section 404: Costs, Earnings Quality, and Stock Prices 
Abstract:
 This paper exploits a natural quasi-experiment to isolate the effects that
 were uniquely due to the Sarbanes-Oxley Act (SOX): U.S. firms with a
 public float under $75 million could delay Section 404 compliance, and
 foreign firms under $700 million could delay the auditor's attestation
 requirement. As designed, Section 404 led to conservative reported
 earnings, but also imposed real costs. On net, SOX compliance reduced the
 market value of small firms. Copyright (c) 2010 the American Finance Association. 
